---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Navigation from '../../components/Navigation.astro';
import { t } from '../../i18n/translations';
import '../../styles/global.css';

const lang = 'en';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout title="Down the Rabbit Hole | Research Journey">
  <Navigation lang={lang} currentPath="/journey" />

  <main class="min-h-screen bg-[#FFF9ED]">
    <!-- Hero Section -->
    <section class="py-16 px-6">
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
        <!-- Breadcrumb -->
        <div class="mb-6">
          <a href={base + "journey"} class="text-sm text-[#003049] hover:text-[#780000] transition-colors inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 font-figtree font-medium">
            <svg class="w-3 h-3 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M15 19l-7-7 7-7"></path>
            </svg>
            Back to Research Journey
          </a>
        </div>

        <!-- Title -->
        <div class="mb-8">
          <div class="text-sm font-semibold text-[#780000] mb-3 uppercase tracking-wide font-figtree">Phase 1</div>
          <h1 class="font-figtree text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-[#003049] mb-4">Down the Rabbit Hole</h1>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Main Content -->
    <section class="py-16 px-6">
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto space-y-12">

        <!-- 1. The Starting Point -->
        <div class="relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg" style="clip-path: polygon(0 0, calc(100% - 32px) 0, 100% 32px, 100% 100%, 0 100%);">
          <div class="grid grid-cols-12">
            <div class="col-span-3 bg-[#780000] p-10 flex items-center justify-center">
              <div class="font-figtree text-7xl font-black text-[#FFF9ED]" style="writing-mode: vertical-rl; text-orientation: mixed; letter-spacing: -0.05em;">01</div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-span-9 bg-[#FFF9ED] p-10 border-4 border-[#780000] border-l-0">
              <h2 class="font-figtree text-4xl font-bold text-[#003049] mb-6" style="text-wrap: balance; letter-spacing: -0.02em;">The Puzzle</h2>
              <div class="space-y-4">
                <p class="font-figtree text-lg text-[#003049]/80 leading-relaxed">
                  Traditional <em class="italic">game theory</em> says <strong>no one</strong> should trust strangers with their money. The rational move is to keep it. Yet in Berg, Dickhaut, & McCabe's (1995) Trust Game, people invest. Consistently. Across cultures.
                </p>
                <p class="font-figtree text-lg text-[#003049]/80 leading-relaxed">
                  <strong>Why?</strong> Trust is complicated. The literature offered two main explanations:
                </p>
                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mt-6">
                  <div class="bg-[#003049]/5 border border-[#003049]/10 p-4 rounded-lg">
                    <p class="font-figtree font-semibold text-[#780000] mb-2">Social Preferences</p>
                    <p class="font-figtree text-sm text-[#003049]/80">Altruism, reciprocity, fairness norms—we trust because we care about others.</p>
                  </div>
                  <div class="bg-[#003049]/5 border border-[#003049]/10 p-4 rounded-lg">
                    <p class="font-figtree font-semibold text-[#669bbc] mb-2">Risk Attitudes</p>
                    <p class="font-figtree text-sm text-[#003049]/80">Different perceptions of uncertainty—maybe trust is just how we handle social risk.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- 2. The Confusion -->
        <div class="border-l-4 border-[#669bbc] pl-8 py-6">
          <h2 class="font-figtree text-3xl font-bold text-[#003049] mb-6">The Confusion</h2>

          <div class="space-y-6">
            <p class="font-figtree text-lg text-[#003049]/80 leading-relaxed">
              The literature is full of contradictory findings. Two main problems emerged:
            </p>

            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
              <div class="bg-[#780000]/10 border-l-4 border-[#780000] p-6 rounded-r-lg">
                <p class="font-figtree font-bold text-[#780000] mb-3">Risk preferences don't predict trust:</p>
                <p class="font-figtree text-[#003049]/80">Risk attitudes correlate with lottery behavior but <span class="font-bold text-[#780000]">not</span> with trust decisions.</p>
                <p class="font-figtree text-sm text-[#003049]/60 mt-2 italic">Houser et al. (2010), Fairley et al. (2016), Eckel & Wilson (2004), Grapin et al. (2016), Ashraf et al. (2006)</p>
              </div>

              <div class="bg-[#669bbc]/10 border-l-4 border-[#669bbc] p-6 rounded-r-lg">
                <p class="font-figtree font-bold text-[#669bbc] mb-3">Actually, they do:</p>
                <p class="font-figtree text-[#003049]/80">Risk preferences <span class="font-bold text-[#669bbc]">predict</span> trust when measured properly. Omitting risk controls changes regression coefficients.</p>
                <p class="font-figtree text-sm text-[#003049]/60 mt-2 italic">Schechter (2007), Karlan (2005), Chetty et al. (2020), Nguyen (2016)</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-[#003049] p-6 rounded-lg mt-6">
              <p class="font-figtree font-bold text-[#FFF9ED] mb-3">And then there's betrayal aversion:</p>
              <p class="font-figtree text-[#FFF9ED]/90 leading-relaxed">
                People trust <em class="italic">more</em> than their risk preferences suggest (Dunning & Fetchenhauer, 2010; Schlösser et al., 2015), but also require <em class="italic">higher</em> probabilities for social risks than mechanical ones (Bohnet & Zeckhauser, 2004). This gap persists even when probabilities are learned (Rățală et al., 2019).
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-[#780000]/5 border border-[#780000]/20 p-6 rounded-lg mt-6">
              <p class="font-figtree text-lg text-[#003049] leading-relaxed">
                How could smart researchers, running careful experiments, get <em class="italic">contradictory</em> results?
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- 3. The Pattern -->
        <div class="relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg" style="clip-path: polygon(0 0, calc(100% - 32px) 0, 100% 32px, 100% 100%, 0 100%);">
          <div class="grid grid-cols-12">
            <div class="col-span-3 bg-[#003049] p-10 flex items-center justify-center">
              <div class="font-figtree text-7xl font-black text-[#FFF9ED]" style="writing-mode: vertical-rl; text-orientation: mixed; letter-spacing: -0.05em;">02</div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-span-9 bg-[#FFF9ED] p-10 border-4 border-[#003049] border-l-0">
              <h2 class="font-figtree text-4xl font-bold text-[#003049] mb-6" style="text-wrap: balance; letter-spacing: -0.02em;">Then I Saw It</h2>

              <div class="space-y-6">
                <p class="font-figtree text-lg text-[#003049]/80 leading-relaxed">
                  I started tracking what each study actually <em class="italic">did</em>. Not what they concluded—what they <strong>measured</strong>.
                </p>

                <p class="font-figtree text-lg text-[#003049]/80 leading-relaxed">
                  Two methodological problems kept appearing:
                </p>

                <!-- Problem 1: Stakes & Probabilities -->
                <div class="bg-[#780000]/5 border border-[#780000]/20 rounded-lg p-6">
                  <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                    <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-12 h-12 bg-[#780000] rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-[#FFF9ED] font-bold text-xl">
                      1
                    </div>
                    <div class="flex-1">
                      <h3 class="font-figtree text-xl font-semibold text-[#780000] mb-3">Different Stakes, Different Probabilities</h3>
                      <p class="font-figtree text-[#003049]/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                        Stakes and probability ranges <strong>varied wildly</strong> across studies. Some used $5 bets, others $100. Some tested 10% vs 90% probabilities, others 40% vs 60%.
                      </p>
                      <div class="bg-[#FFF9ED] border border-[#780000]/20 p-4 rounded">
                        <p class="font-figtree text-sm text-[#003049]/80 italic">
                          Wait. <strong>Prospect Theory</strong> has different parameters for different contexts. What if low stakes show risk &gt; trust, but high stakes show trust &gt; risk? What if they were testing <em class="italic">different parts</em> of the same theory?
                        </p>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Problem 2: Mismatched Uncertainty -->
                <div class="bg-[#669bbc]/5 border border-[#669bbc]/20 rounded-lg p-6">
                  <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                    <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-12 h-12 bg-[#669bbc] rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-[#FFF9ED] font-bold text-xl">
                      2
                    </div>
                    <div class="flex-1">
                      <h3 class="font-figtree text-xl font-semibold text-[#669bbc] mb-3">Mismatched Uncertainty Levels</h3>
                      <p class="font-figtree text-[#003049]/80 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                        This was the big one. Studies were comparing <strong>apples to oranges</strong>:
                      </p>
                      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                        <div class="bg-[#FFF9ED] border-2 border-[#780000] p-4 rounded-lg">
                          <p class="font-figtree font-bold text-[#780000] mb-2">Risk Condition</p>
                          <ul class="space-y-1 font-figtree text-sm text-[#003049]/80">
                            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                              <span class="text-[#780000] mt-0.5">✓</span>
                              <span>Known outcomes</span>
                            </li>
                            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                              <span class="text-[#780000] mt-0.5">✓</span>
                              <span><strong>Known probabilities</strong></span>
                            </li>
                          </ul>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-[#FFF9ED] border-2 border-[#669bbc] p-4 rounded-lg">
                          <p class="font-figtree font-bold text-[#669bbc] mb-2">Trust Condition</p>
                          <ul class="space-y-1 font-figtree text-sm text-[#003049]/80">
                            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                              <span class="text-[#669bbc] mt-0.5">✓</span>
                              <span>Known outcomes</span>
                            </li>
                            <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                              <span class="text-[#669bbc] mt-0.5">✗</span>
                              <span><strong>No objective probabilities</strong></span>
                            </li>
                          </ul>
                        </div>
                      </div>
                      <p class="font-figtree text-sm text-[#003049]/70 mt-4 italic">
                        In risk, you know the dice is fair. In trust, you have no idea what the other person will do. These are <em>fundamentally different types of uncertainty</em>.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- 4. The Breakthrough -->
        <div class="bg-[#003049] px-8 py-10 rounded-lg">
          <h2 class="font-figtree text-3xl font-bold text-[#FFF9ED] mb-6">The Breakthrough</h2>
          <div class="space-y-6">
            <p class="font-figtree text-xl text-[#FFF9ED] leading-relaxed font-semibold">
              What if the contradiction wasn't <em class="italic">theoretical</em>, but <em class="italic">methodological</em>?
            </p>

            <p class="font-figtree text-lg text-[#FFF9ED]/90 leading-relaxed">
              Every study was testing something slightly different. Different stakes, different probabilities, different types of uncertainty.
            </p>

            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#669bbc] pl-6 py-2">
              <p class="font-figtree text-[#FFF9ED] font-semibold mb-3">The real question became:</p>
              <p class="font-figtree text-lg text-[#FFF9ED]/90 leading-relaxed">
                Can <strong>Prospect Theory</strong>—the Nobel Prize-winning framework for risk—explain trust behavior when we <em class="italic">properly control</em> for stakes, probabilities, and uncertainty levels?
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- 5. The Framework: Prospect Theory -->
        <div class="border-l-4 border-[#780000] pl-8 py-6">
          <h2 class="font-figtree text-3xl font-bold text-[#003049] mb-6">The Framework: Prospect Theory</h2>

          <div class="space-y-6">
            <p class="font-figtree text-lg text-[#003049]/80 leading-relaxed">
              Kahneman & Tversky's <strong>Prospect Theory</strong> (Nobel Prize 2002) explains how people make decisions under <em class="italic">risk</em>. Three core principles:
            </p>

            <div class="space-y-4">
              <!-- Loss Aversion -->
              <div class="border-l-4 border-[#780000] pl-6 py-4">
                <h3 class="font-figtree text-lg font-bold text-[#780000] mb-2">Loss Aversion (λ)</h3>
                <p class="font-figtree text-[#003049]/80 leading-relaxed">
                  Losses hurt <strong>more than gains feel good</strong>. Losing $10 feels worse than gaining $10 feels good. This asymmetry drives behavior.
                </p>
              </div>

              <!-- Diminishing Sensitivity -->
              <div class="border-l-4 border-[#669bbc] pl-6 py-4">
                <h3 class="font-figtree text-lg font-bold text-[#669bbc] mb-2">Diminishing Sensitivity (α)</h3>
                <p class="font-figtree text-[#003049]/80 leading-relaxed">
                  The difference between $0 and $10 <strong>feels bigger</strong> than between $100 and $110. We're sensitive to changes near our reference point.
                </p>
              </div>

              <!-- Probability Weighting -->
              <div class="border-l-4 border-[#003049] pl-6 py-4">
                <h3 class="font-figtree text-lg font-bold text-[#003049] mb-2">Probability Weighting (γ⁺ for gains, γ⁻ for losses)</h3>
                <p class="font-figtree text-[#003049]/80 leading-relaxed">
                  We <strong>overweight small probabilities</strong> (lottery tickets!) and <strong>underweight large ones</strong>. A 1% chance feels bigger than it is. A 99% chance feels less certain. This distortion can differ between potential gains and potential losses.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-[#003049]/5 border border-[#003049]/10 p-6 rounded-lg">
              <p class="font-figtree text-sm text-[#003049]/80 italic">
                These principles explain gambling, insurance, stock market behavior. But nobody had rigorously tested if the <strong>same math</strong> explains trusting people—when we control for the type of uncertainty.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- 6. The Path Forward -->
        <div class="bg-[#003049] px-8 py-8 rounded-lg">
          <h2 class="font-figtree text-3xl font-bold text-[#FFF9ED] mb-6">What Needed to Happen</h2>
          <div class="space-y-6">
            <p class="font-figtree text-lg text-[#FFF9ED]/90 leading-relaxed">
              To answer this question properly, I needed:
            </p>
            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-[#669bbc] rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-[#FFF9ED] font-bold text-sm">
                  1
                </div>
                <div>
                  <p class="font-figtree text-[#FFF9ED] font-semibold mb-1">Matched Probability Distributions</p>
                  <p class="font-figtree text-[#FFF9ED]/80 text-sm">Trust and Risk games with <strong>identical</strong> outcome probabilities. Same stakes, same ranges.</p>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-[#669bbc] rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-[#FFF9ED] font-bold text-sm">
                  2
                </div>
                <div>
                  <p class="font-figtree text-[#FFF9ED] font-semibold mb-1">Controlled Uncertainty</p>
                  <p class="font-figtree text-[#FFF9ED]/80 text-sm">Match the <em>type</em> of uncertainty. If risk has known probabilities, trust needs known probabilities too.</p>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-[#669bbc] rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-[#FFF9ED] font-bold text-sm">
                  3
                </div>
                <div>
                  <p class="font-figtree text-[#FFF9ED] font-semibold mb-1">Optimal Experimental Design</p>
                  <p class="font-figtree text-[#FFF9ED]/80 text-sm">Use Fisher Information to select highly informative trials that reveal Prospect Theory parameters across both contexts.</p>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-[#669bbc] rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-[#FFF9ED] font-bold text-sm">
                  4
                </div>
                <div>
                  <p class="font-figtree text-[#FFF9ED] font-semibold mb-1">Comprehensive Model Comparison</p>
                  <p class="font-figtree text-[#FFF9ED]/80 text-sm">Test 16 nested models. Let the data tell us which parameters differ between trust and risk.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-[#FFF9ED]/10 border border-[#FFF9ED]/20 p-4 rounded mt-6">
              <p class="font-figtree text-[#FFF9ED]/90 italic">
                That's what Phase 2 and 3 are about. Building the experiment that can finally answer this question.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Key References -->
        <div class="border-l-4 border-[#780000] pl-8 py-6">
          <h2 class="font-figtree text-3xl font-bold text-[#003049] mb-6">Key References</h2>
          <div class="space-y-3 font-figtree text-sm text-[#003049]/80">
            <a href={base + "references#berg-1995"} class="block bg-[#FFF9ED] border border-[#003049]/10 p-4 rounded hover:bg-[#669bbc]/5 transition-colors">
              <strong class="text-[#003049]">Berg, J., Dickhaut, J., & McCabe, K. (1995).</strong> Trust, reciprocity, and social history. <em class="italic">Games and Economic Behavior</em>, 10(1), 122-142.
              <p class="text-xs text-[#003049]/60 mt-1">The original Trust Game. The puzzle that started it all.</p>
            </a>
            <a href={base + "references#kahneman-1979"} class="block bg-[#FFF9ED] border border-[#003049]/10 p-4 rounded hover:bg-[#669bbc]/5 transition-colors">
              <strong class="text-[#003049]">Kahneman, D., & Tversky, A. (1979).</strong> Prospect theory: An analysis of decision under risk. <em class="italic">Econometrica</em>, 47(2), 263-291.
              <p class="text-xs text-[#003049]/60 mt-1">The Nobel Prize-winning framework. The math I'm testing on trust.</p>
            </a>
            <a href={base + "references#houser-2010"} class="block bg-[#FFF9ED] border border-[#003049]/10 p-4 rounded hover:bg-[#669bbc]/5 transition-colors">
              <strong class="text-[#003049]">Houser, D., Schunk, D., & Winter, J. (2010).</strong> Distinguishing trust from risk: An anatomy of the investment game. <em class="italic">Journal of Economic Behavior & Organization</em>, 74(1-2), 72-81.
              <p class="text-xs text-[#003049]/60 mt-1">Risk preferences don't predict trust decisions.</p>
            </a>
            <a href={base + "references#schechter-2007"} class="block bg-[#FFF9ED] border border-[#003049]/10 p-4 rounded hover:bg-[#669bbc]/5 transition-colors">
              <strong class="text-[#003049]">Schechter, L. (2007).</strong> Traditional trust measurement and the risk confound: An experiment in rural Paraguay. <em class="italic">Journal of Economic Behavior & Organization</em>, 62(2), 272-292.
              <p class="text-xs text-[#003049]/60 mt-1">Omitting risk controls changes regression coefficients significantly.</p>
            </a>
            <a href={base + "references#bohnet-2004"} class="block bg-[#FFF9ED] border border-[#003049]/10 p-4 rounded hover:bg-[#669bbc]/5 transition-colors">
              <strong class="text-[#003049]">Bohnet, I., & Zeckhauser, R. (2004).</strong> Trust, risk and betrayal. <em class="italic">Journal of Economic Behavior & Organization</em>, 55(4), 467-484.
              <p class="text-xs text-[#003049]/60 mt-1">People require higher probabilities for social risks than mechanical ones.</p>
            </a>
            <a href={base + "references#ratala-2019"} class="block bg-[#FFF9ED] border border-[#003049]/10 p-4 rounded hover:bg-[#669bbc]/5 transition-colors">
              <strong class="text-[#003049]">Rățală, C., Galvan, E., & Sanfey, A. G. (2019).</strong> Trust and risk revisited. Unpublished manuscript.
              <p class="text-xs text-[#003049]/60 mt-1">The gap between trust and risk persists even when probabilities are learned.</p>
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <!-- Footer -->
  <footer class="py-12 px-6 bg-[#003049] text-[#FFF9ED]">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto text-center">
      <p class="font-figtree text-lg mb-4 font-semibold">Himalaya Girard</p>
      <p class="font-figtree text-[#669bbc] mb-6">{t('footer.position', lang)}</p>
      <p class="font-figtree text-sm text-[#669bbc]/70 mt-8">
        {t('footer.rights', lang)}
      </p>
    </div>
  </footer>
</Layout>
